  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Respect Education and Radio Teaching DRC</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Direct target groups:
- 52 teachers will develop better teaching skills 
- better quality education at 26 primary school in the Walungu district (east Congo), reaching over 3.000 children

Indirect target groups:
- teachers at other Primary Schools in DR Congo, who listen to the radio broadcasts and/or who benefit from the handbook on didactics that is being developed through this project. 350 Copies of the manual will be distributed.
- children in DR Congo reached through these teachers</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Specific goals are:
- to improve teaching skills (didactics, pedagogy) of 52 teachers at 26 schools in the Walungu district in DR Congo
- to develop radio modules and an interactive teachers manual. Crucial content is about: active and participative teaching, and Respect education. 
Participative teaching involves putting the student at the centre of the learning, stimulating equal treatment and engagement of all students, especially girls.
- to make the school environment more secure and safe and to increase the quality of education
- Improve student performance and reduce dropout rates</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">lThis program aims at improving the quality of education by capacity building of 52 teachers at 26 schools in Walungu (South Kivu, DRC). The capacity building has two components: - Respect Education Methodology: focussed on more mutual respect between children and appreciation of differences - Active and participative way of teaching: stimulating children to participate actively during lessons 
